Key Findings: D100 Teachers Are Paid Less at Every Career Stage

  • Starting Teachers: New D100 teachers earn between $2,124 and $5,007 less than peers in D98 and D99, depending on education level. This immediate disadvantage makes recruitment extremely difficult.
  • Mid-Career Teachers (10 Years): At the 10-year mark, when teachers have proven their value, gaps widen dramatically. Bachelor's-level teachers in D99 earn $10,461 more than D100. Master's-level teachers are $3,475-$5,952 behind.
  • Veteran Teachers (20-25 Years): Our most experienced educators face the largest gaps: $6,113-$8,120 behind D98 and $11,072-$13,479 behind D99. These are the teachers who mentor new staff and carry institutional knowledge.
  • Overall Competitiveness: On average across all education levels and career stages, D100 pays 5.7% less than North Berwyn D98 and 10.5% less than Cicero D99.
  • Lifetime Impact: Over a 30-year career, D100 teachers with a Master's degree lose between $43,000 (vs D98) and $292,000 (vs D99). For teachers with advanced credentials (Master's+45), the losses range from $161,000 to $220,000.

üîç CRITICAL FINDING: The Longer You Stay, The Further Behind You Fall

The salary gap between D100 and peer districts INCREASES as teachers gain more experience. This creates a structural disincentive for longevity in D100:

  • At Year 1 (Bachelor's): D100 is behind by $2,124-$4,516
  • At Year 10 (Bachelor's): D100 is behind by $239-$10,461
  • At Year 13 (Bachelor's): D100 is behind by $1,864-$11,791
  • At Year 20 (Master's): D100 is behind by $4,860-$13,479
  • At Year 25 (Master's): D100 is behind by $6,113-$11,072

Translation: The district's salary structure punishes loyalty. Teachers who stay in D100 see their compensation fall further behind peers each year they remain. This is the opposite of what a retention-focused compensation system should do.

Why This Matters: Impact on Students and District

  • Recruitment Crisis: When qualified candidates receive offers from multiple districts, they will consistently choose D98 or D99 for $2,000-$5,000 more per year starting salary. D100 becomes the "backup" choice.
  • Retention Risk: Mid-career teachers (10-15 years) are the most mobile and attractive to other districts. They can transfer to D98 or D99 with full seniority recognition. Why would they stay when they're losing $4,000-$10,000 annually?
  • Institutional Knowledge Loss: Veteran teachers don't just teach‚Äîthey mentor new teachers, lead curriculum development, serve on committees, and embody the district's culture. Losing them to D98/D99 means starting over repeatedly.
  • Student Impact: D100 serves 74-79% economically disadvantaged students. These high-needs students benefit most from experienced, stable teaching staff. Teacher turnover is particularly harmful to our community.
  • Equity Issue: D98, D99, and D100 serve similar demographics‚Äîpredominantly Hispanic, working-class communities with comparable student needs. There is no "wealth gap" justifying pay differences. D99 even has slightly higher free/reduced lunch rates than D100, yet pays teachers significantly more.

‚ö†Ô∏è Bottom Line for Negotiations

D100 teachers are not asking for extravagant raises or to be the highest-paid in the region. We are asking for parity with our true peer districts‚Äîneighboring communities with similar demographics, similar student needs, and similar resources.

If D98 and D99 can afford to pay their teachers fairly, D100 can too.

About This Data

  • Source: Current salary schedules from all three districts, agreed upon by both bargaining teams
  • D100 Schedule: 2025-2026 school year
  • D98 & D99 Schedules: Current year schedules

üìà Visual Analysis: Salary Comparisons

These visualizations make clear patterns in the data: D100 consistently pays less than peer districts, and gaps increase with teacher experience.

Comprehensive Comparison: D100 vs Peer Average & Maximum

üéØ Key Takeaways:

  • The blue D100 line runs consistently BELOW the orange peer average across all career stages
  • Gaps exist at every single step on the salary schedule‚Äînot just at entry or top-of-scale
  • The green "Peer Max" line shows that some teachers in peer districts earn significantly more at each step
  • KEY INSIGHT: D100 is not competitive anywhere on the schedule

All Three Districts Compared

üéØ Key Takeaways:

  • Both D98 (purple) and D99 (orange) exceed D100 (blue) at nearly every career stage
  • D99 gaps are particularly large for mid-career and veteran teachers
  • D98 provides more modest but consistent advantages throughout the schedule
  • KEY INSIGHT: D100 is the "low bidder" in our peer group

Career Progression by Education Level

üéØ Key Takeaways:

  • At ALL education levels (Bachelor's, Master's, Master's+32, Master's+45), D100 falls behind
  • Gaps widen as teachers gain experience‚Äîloyalty is financially penalized
  • Higher education credentials show larger gaps, especially in comparison to D99
  • KEY INSIGHT: The gap at 10-25 years is substantial and growing

Dollar Gaps at Critical Career Stages

üéØ Key Takeaways:

  • Starting teachers: Already $2K-$5K behind on day one
  • Mid-career (10 years): Gaps widen to $4K-$10K annually
  • Veterans (20-25 years): Largest gaps of $6K-$13K per year
  • KEY INSIGHT: Veterans face the strongest financial incentive to leave for D98/D99

30-Year Career Earnings Impact

üéØ Key Takeaways:

  • Master's degree teachers lose $43K-$292K over a full career vs peers
  • Master's+45 teachers lose $161K-$220K over their careers
  • These losses represent retirement savings, home equity, or college tuition for teachers' own children
  • KEY INSIGHT: The cumulative cost of staying in D100 is staggering

Visual Evidence Summary

These charts provide clear, undeniable evidence that:

  1. D100 is behind at EVERY step on the salary schedule‚Äînot just isolated positions
  2. Gaps INCREASE with experience‚Äîveteran teachers face the largest disadvantages
  3. Both peer districts pay more‚Äîthis isn't about one "wealthy outlier" district
  4. Cumulative lifetime losses are massive‚Äîhundreds of thousands of dollars over a career
  5. A longevity bonus is justified‚Äîcurrent structure penalizes teachers who stay in D100
